[5] Yemen, stray dogs, human
Date: Mon 18 Sep 2017
Source: Yemeni Medical Journal [in Arabic, trans. Mod.MM, edited]
http://ye-mj.net/news_details.php?sid=1798


Residents of the capital Sanaa and other governorates are suffering from the daily attacks of stray dogs which have raised the incidence rate of suspected rabies to 30-40 cases/day. According to the rabies control officer at the Republican hospital in Sanaa, the number of rabies cases this year, 2017, has reached 248 cases with 16 deaths among them. He attributed this rise in human rabies cases to the absence of rabies control programme activities due to lack of funding.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

The human rabies cases statistics described above in Sanaa, the Yemeni capital, illustrate the need for effective control efforts directed to minimize the risk of human exposure, which seems to be inevitable due to the collapsing health infrastructure. The rabies related fatalities mentioned above may be due to the lack of post-exposure prophylaxis for the victims plus the absence of a rabies vaccination program for animals, especially dogs. - Mod.MM

The statement "the number of rabies cases this year, 2017, has reached 248 cases with 16 deaths among them" is in need of some discourse. A human rabies "case" would generally mean that the patient has been suffering clinical signs suspected to be rabies. Such cases are practically always fatal. In the current event, the reporter probably attributed the term "cases" to people exposed to rabies (eg bitten by a rabid animal). The number of such has been, according to the above report, 248. The number of "cases" was, at the time of the reporting, 16 and the incidence rate, at the time of the reporting, 6.45 percent. This rate could increase if, during that point in time, some of the 248 exposed persons were incubating the disease. - Mod.AS]

******
[6] Zambia, dairy cow, human exposure
Date: Fri 15 Sep 2017
Source: The Chronicle (Zimbabwe) [edited]
http://www.chronicle.co.zw/rabies-from-a-cow-infected-beasts-milk-puts-9-at-risk/


A family of 9 in Nkayi has been put under surveillance as it is feared to have contracted rabies after consuming milk from a cow that had been bitten by a stray rabid dog.

The family admitted to have milked the cow for over a month until it died last week [week of Sun 3 Sep 2017] after it had been bitten by the dog.

Rabies in humans is fatal in most cases and infected people slowly become paralysed and eventually slip into a coma and die.

Nkayi District Medical Officer Dr Thabani Moyo said the family reported to the Department of Veterinary Services after their cow suddenly died [comment] and tests confirmed that it had succumbed to rabies. Dr Moyo said even though the family members are not showing any signs and symptoms of rabies, there are fears that they contracted it after milking an infected cow and consuming its milk for a month.

"The family members who are not yet showing signs and symptoms of rabies are under surveillance," said Dr Moyo.

He said environmental health technicians are monitoring the family which has since purchased the anti-rabies vaccine. Dr Moyo said it can take between 2 months and 6 years before humans can show signs and symptoms of rabies.

"Rabies can be contracted through consuming products from a rabid animal," said Dr Moyo.

"The family admitted to have been milking the cow since August [2017] until it died.

"They reported the matter to the veterinary services who took samples from the carcass [comment] which tested rabies positive. We received the report and advised the family to procure treatment as it was possible that they could have contracted the disease."

Dr Moyo said it was unfortunate that there is no rabies vaccine in the district but the family was advised to purchase the vaccine elsewhere.

"A family member, Mr Roni Ndlovu has since managed to secure the rabies vaccine for his family in Bulawayo, costing up to USD 45 per full course per person," he said.

Matabeleland North Provincial Medical Director Dr Nyasha Masuka urged all people who own dogs to ensure that they are vaccinated.

"All stray dogs should be reported to the local Department of Livestock and Veterinary Services so that they can be put down. If anyone is bitten by a dog they should find out the vaccination status of the dog from the owner.

"If the dog is not vaccinated or if people are not sure, they should go to the nearest health facility for treatment and rabies vaccination.

"Other animals like donkeys and cattle can bite human beings if they are infected with rabies and people should quickly report such unusual behavior by domestic animals," he said.

[Byline: Whinsley Masara]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

According to the report, the suspected cow was milked for over a month after it had been bitten by a "stray rabid dog", then died "suddenly" leading the family to report the case to the Department of Veterinary Services. This deserves some deliberation:
1. Generally, rabies infected animals - including cattle - show, during the final stages of their life, some clinical signs caused by the affection of their central nervous system (brain). In milking animals, this may be accompanied by drop in the milk yield, which, by itself, is also a sign of disease. "Sudden" death may occur but is exceptional.
2. Human cases due to non-bite exposures to rabies are very rare. Scratches, abrasions, open wounds, and mucous membranes contaminated with saliva or other potentially infectious material (such as brain tissue) from a rabid animal constitute non-bite exposures. Inhalation of aerosolized rabies virus is also a potential non-bite route of exposure, but other than laboratory workers, most people are unlikely to encounter aerosolized rabies virus. There are no published studies that have demonstrated the presence of rabies virus in cow milk. Although transmission of rabies virus from consuming unpasteurized milk from an infected animal is theoretically possible, no human has ever been reported to develop rabies via this route. Milk that has been heat pasteurized presents no risk for rabies virus transmission (https://www.cdc.gov/rabies/resources/news/2005-12-23.html).
3.Those who have attended the rabid cow during her last week of life could have been exposed to the virus which is particularly present in the saliva. The decision to apply post-exposure treatment is fully justified and necessary.
4. When a farm animal is known to have been bitten by a wild animal, or by a dog suspected to be rabid, the incident deserves immediate reporting to the veterinary authorities who are entrusted with the issuance of relevant measures/guidelines. In any case, the bitten animal should remain under veterinary observation for at least 3 months. In some countries, the law allows the slaughter of the exposed animal within a limited time-frame (less than a week) immediately after the incident; in case not slaughtered - the bitten animal should be kept under observation, while forbidding its sale/movement to other location(s).

According to the report, "samples from the cow's carcass tested rabies positive". It may be assumed that the tested tissue was sampled from the cow's brain, the only animal tissue appropriate for rabies testing. - Mod.AS

